          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Charleston</placeName>
                                        <date>20<hi rend="sup">th</hi> August 1850</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(3)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">My dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(5)">Enclosed you will find, put in a<lb/> poetical
                                        garb, one of those interesting tales of which the Talmud
                                        abounds,<lb/> and whose simplicity and moral tendency may
                                        have some beneficial<lb/> influence upon those of our
                                        people, who have no access to venerated<lb/> books, which
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName> claims as an
                                        inheritance from their pious ancestors,<lb/> and the
                                        preservation of which has cost them so much. If you think
                                        them<lb/> worth publishing in the Occident, and agreeable to
                                        you, I will use<lb/> my <sic>leasure</sic> moments for the
                                        purpose of furnishing you with a series<lb/> of them, if
                                        possible; one, monthly. You can head them, “Talmudical<lb/>
                                        Tales.” Please let me have an answer to this. What do you
                                        think<lb/> of <persName>Dr Wise's</persName> course? By the
                                        by, I know from good authority that<lb/> he could produce
                                        here no Diploma, except the <add>מורינו</add>. Upon
                                        which<lb/> the <placeName>Hazel Street</placeName>
                                        congregation, with equal right doctorized <persName>Mr
                                                  Eckman.</persName><lb/> It appears that the
                                        congregations, not satisfied with the simple<lb/> Revd, have
                                        assumed the authority of conferring Doctordom upon<lb/> any
                                        individual who happens to be their minister If a
                                                  <add>מורינו</add><lb/> bestowed by any Rabbi or
                                        Beth dun entitles the possessor to be<lb/> considered <hi
                                                  rend="underline">Doctor of Divinity</hi>, (as
                                                  <persName>Wise</persName> impertinently signed his
                                        name in the last<lb/> occident) we may <hi rend="underline"
                                                  >all</hi> assume it. No Rabbi in
                                                  <placeName>Germany</placeName>,
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName>, etc.<lb/> is
                                        Doctor of divinity, nor do they assume the power of
                                        conferring it<lb/> upon others. <persName>Drs
                                                  Adler</persName>, <persName>Frankel</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Geiger Raphael</persName>
                                        <sic>ect</sic>, are all Doctors of<lb/> Phylosophy. If
                                        matters remain so, <persName>Dr Wise</persName> as well as
                                        the <placeName>Hazel Street</placeName><lb/> congregation
                                        will soon fabricate sufficient Doctors to colonize the<lb/>
                                        world</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The cause of orthodoxy is fast declining in this city.<lb/>
                                        <persName>Pozenanskis</persName> resignation and
                                                  <persName>Eckman's</persName> pretending to be
                                        a<lb/> strict orthodox Jew, have charged affairs
                                        considerably. Many<lb/> of those who were formerly Champions
                                        in our cause have found,<lb/> after mature reflection, that
                                        all their zeal was based on<lb/> party spirit, and by no
                                        means on true religious principles.<lb/> Many say now
                                                  <add>אלכה ואשובה אל אישי הראשון כי טוב לי אז
                                                  מעתה</add>. The fact is, that<lb/> infidelism and
                                        indifference have taken such root here, that, I<lb/>
                                        apprehend they will never be <sic>erazed</sic>.
                                                  <persName>Pozenanski</persName> left a<lb/> deep,
                                        venomous string behind him which is calculated to
                                        poison<lb/> the latest generations. You can form an idea of
                                        the <placeName>Charleston</placeName><lb/> orthodoxy, when
                                        ever <add>שחיטה</add> is neglected. Our Shochet is an old
                                        man,<lb/> whose nervous temperament, together an occasional
                                        attack<lb/> of Rheumatism causes his hands to tremble
                                        considerably, which<lb/> according to our Law, disqualifies
                                        him from being <add>שוחט</add> and yet<lb/> with all my
                                        efforts, I could not induce the congregation even<lb/> to
                                        have him examined, although he has not been examined for<lb/>
                                        <hi rend="underline">many</hi> years, and has had almost
                                        every year a severe spell<lb/> of sickness. I know he is
                                        incapable. Besides, he never examines the<lb/> lungs by
                                        sight, he is satisfied by putting his hands in the
                                        animal<lb/> and declaring <add>כשר</add>, a proceeding which
                                        is entirely against<lb/> law, as it is an impossibility for
                                        any man, no matter how proficient<lb/> he may be, to declare
                                        an animal to be <add>כשר</add> without examining it<lb/>
                                        closely, <add>למראה עיניו ישפוט רק</add>. Many other things
                                        have transpired lately<lb/> which convince me that Orthodoxy
                                        is loosing ground rapidly,<lb/> And that the congregation
                                        Shearit Israel may soon die an<lb/> untimely death. I think
                                        nothing can save it, and if matters<lb/> remain as they are,
                                        and as they will probably be, my stay here will be</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>of short duration. I hope that your affairs will terminate<lb/>
                                        more satisfactorily than you anticipated, at least this the
                                        opinion<lb/> of your friends here. It is at the same time
                                        hoped, and expected<lb/> that you will yield to conciliatory
                                        measures. Hoping that<lb/> this may reach you in the
                                        enjoyment of good health and content<lb/>ment, and wishing
                                        you <add>כתיבה וחתימה טובה</add> I remain</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">Yrs Truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(7)">
                                        <persName role="author">Jacob Rosenfeld</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>The</p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
                              </p>
